Section 1:
1 L.D. 428
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 CRIMINAL JUSTICE AND PUBLIC SAFETY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 282, L.D. 428, “An Act Regarding the
10 State Forensic Service”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act to Require Electronic Delivery of Mental Examination Records of Criminal
13 Defendants'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
15 following:
16 'Sec. 1. 15 MRSA §101-C, sub-§6 is enacted to read:
17 6. Method of production. A record or copy of a record sent by regular mail to a
18 person or entity pursuant to subsection 1 must also be sent to that person or entity by
19 electronic means, if feasible, the same day as the record is sent by regular mail.
20 Sec. 2. 15 MRSA §101-D, sub-§1, ¶A, as enacted by PL 2009, c. 268, §3, is
21 amended to read:
22 A. Upon motion by the defendant or by the State, or upon its own motion, a court
23 having jurisdiction in any criminal case may for cause shown order that the defendant
24 be examined by the State Forensic Service for evaluation of the defendant's
25 competency to proceed. When ordered to evaluate a defendant under this paragraph,
26 the State Forensic Service shall promptly examine the defendant and report its initial
27 determination regarding the defendant’s competency to proceed to the court. The State
28 Forensic Service shall send the report to the court by electronic means. If, based upon
29 its examination, the State Forensic Service concludes that further examination is
30 necessary to fully evaluate the defendant's competency to proceed, the report must so
31 state and must set forth recommendations as to the nature and scope of any further
32 examination. The court shall forward any report filed by the State Forensic Service to
33 the defendant or the defendant's attorney and to the attorney for the State.
34 Sec. 3. 15 MRSA §101-D, sub-§1, ¶C, as enacted by PL 2009, c. 268, §3, is
35 amended to read:
Page 1 - 132LR1939(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 282, L.D. 428
1 C. If the report submitted pursuant to paragraph A recommends further evaluation of
2 the defendant or upon motion by the defendant or by the State for good cause shown,
3 the court may order further evaluation of the defendant by the State Forensic Service.
4 Any order for further evaluation may designate the specialty of the person to perform
5 the evaluation. In addition, if at any time during a criminal proceeding an issue of
6 competency to proceed arises with respect to a defendant initially determined to be
7 competent, the court may order such further examination by the State Forensic Service
8 as the court finds necessary and appropriate. The State Forensic Service shall send any
9 further report under this paragraph to the court by electronic means. The court shall
10 forward any further report filed by the State Forensic Service to the defendant or the
11 defendant’s attorney and to the attorney for the State.
12 Sec. 4. 15 MRSA §101-D, sub-§2, ¶A, as amended by PL 2015, c. 431, §4, is
13 further amended by amending subparagraph (1) to read:
14 (1) When ordered to evaluate a defendant under this paragraph, the State Forensic
15 Service shall promptly examine the defendant and the circumstances of the crime
16 and provide a report of its evaluation to the court. The State Forensic Service shall
17 send the report to the court by electronic means. If, based upon its examination, the
18 State Forensic Service concludes that further examination is necessary to fully
19 evaluate the defendant's mental state at the time of the crime, the report must so
20 state and must set forth recommendations as to the nature and scope of any further
21 examination.
22 Sec. 5. 15 MRSA §101-D, sub-§2, ¶D, as amended by PL 2015, c. 431, §4, is
23 further amended to read:
24 D. If the report submitted pursuant to paragraph A recommends further evaluation of
25 the defendant or upon motion by the defendant or by the State for good cause shown,
26 the court may order further evaluation of the defendant by the State Forensic Service.
27 An order for further evaluation may designate the specialty of the person to perform
28 the evaluation. The State Forensic Service shall send any further report under this
29 paragraph to the court by electronic means. The court shall forward any further report
30 filed by the State Forensic Service to the defendant or the defendant's attorney and,
31 unless the defendant had objected to the order for examination, to the attorney for the
32 State.
33 The court may order an examination under this paragraph over the objection of the
34 defendant, but any report filed by the State Forensic Service must be impounded and
35 may not be shared with the attorney for the State, unless with reference to criminal
36 responsibility the defendant enters a plea of not criminally responsible by reason of
37 insanity or with reference to an abnormal condition of mind the defendant provides
38 notice to the attorney for the State of the intention to introduce testimony as to the
39 defendant’s abnormal condition of mind pursuant to the Maine Rules of Unified
40 Criminal Procedure, Rule 16A(a).
41 Sec. 6. 15 MRSA §101-D, sub-§3, ¶A, as enacted by PL 2009, c. 268, §3, is
42 amended to read:
43 A. Upon motion by the defendant or by the State or upon its own motion a court having
44 jurisdiction in any criminal case may for cause shown order that the defendant be
45 examined by the State Forensic Service for evaluation with respect to any issue
Page 2 - 132LR1939(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 282, L.D. 428
416 necessary for determination in the case, including the appropriate sentence. The court's
427 order shall set forth the issue or issues to be addressed by the State Forensic Service.
438 When ordered to evaluate a defendant under this paragraph, the State Forensic Service
449 shall promptly examine the defendant and the circumstances relevant to the issues
550 identified in the court's order and report to the court regarding the defendant's mental
561 condition as it pertains to those issues. The State Forensic Service shall send the report
572 to the court by electronic means. Prior to a verdict or finding of guilty or prior to
583 acceptance of a plea of guilty or nolo contendere, the court may not order examination
594 under this subsection over the objection of the defendant unless the defendant has
1505 asserted, or intends to assert, the defendant's mental condition as a basis for an
1516 objection, a defense or for mitigation at sentencing. The court shall forward any report
1527 filed by the State Forensic Service to the defendant or the defendant's attorney and to
1538 the attorney for the State.
14 Sec. 7. Effective date. This Act takes effect January 1, 2028.'
15 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
16 number to read consecutively.
17 SUMMARY
1188 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, replaces the bill, which
1199 is a concept draft, and changes the title. The amendment requires the State Forensic Service
2200 to send mental examination reports of a defendant accused of a crime to a court by
2211 electronic means. The amendment also requires that when a person or entity that has been
2222 ordered to conduct a mental examination on a criminal defendant requests a record from a
2233 certain entity, that entity must provide the requested records by electronic means, if
2244 feasible, the same day it is sent by regular mail. This legislation does not take effect until
2255 January 1, 2028.
2266 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
2277 (See attached)
